r 15. Epics in Worlds of Performance : A South/Southeast Asian Narrativity -- tChapter 16. Postscript: The Many Worlds of Monsoon Asia -- tBibliography -- tAbout the authors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMonsoon Asia was the first venue of global trade, a zone of encounters, exchanges, and cultural diffusion. This book demonstrates the continuing fertility of the Monsoon Asia perspective as an aid to understanding what South/Southeast Asia, as a connected space, has been in the past and is today. Sixteen tightly knit chapters, written by experts from perspectives ranging from Indology and philology to postcolonial and transnational studies, offer a captivating view of the region, with its rich and variegated history shaped by commonalities in human ecology, cultural forms, and religious practices. The contributions draw upon extensive research and a thorough command of the most recent scholarship. This volume will be an invaluable text for anyone interested in South and Southeast Asia, and for more specialized students in the fields of global and Indian Ocean history, transcultural studies, archaeology, linguistics, and politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aAsian Studies. 4aInternational Relations. 4aSouth Asia. 4aSouth East Asia. 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh  aSouth Asia, Southeast Asia, history, geography, region, Indianization.1 aAcri, Andrea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAmrith, Sunil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArps, Bernard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerenschot, Ward, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlackburn, Anne M., econtributor.4ctb4https